li.p:
The augmented matrix and its reduced row echelon form are
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ -2 \amp 2 \amp 6 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
The linear system corresponding to the reduced row echelon form is
\begin{alignedat}{3} x \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp -1 \\ \amp \amp y \amp {}={} \amp 2 \\ \amp \amp 0 \amp {}={} \amp 0\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
This shows that there is a single solution (-1,2) and that every variable is a basic variable.

We have the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} -1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that all the variables are basic variables and that there is a unique solution: x_1 = -1, x_2=0, and x_3=1.

The augmented matrix and its reduced row echelon form are
\left[\begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 2 \amp -5 \amp -1 \amp -3 \\ -2 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp -2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 9 \amp -7 \\ 0 \amp -1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 4 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This gives the equations
\begin{aligned} x_1 \amp = 2 + x_3 \\ x_2 \amp = -3 + 2x_3 \\ x_4 \amp = -1 \\ \end{aligned}
showing that x_3 is a free variable and x_1, x_2, and x_4 are basic variables. There are therefore infinitely many solutions.

The reduced row echelon form is
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{,}
and there is a single solution. Every variable is basic.

The reduced row echelon form is
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
All the variables are basic so there is a unique solution: x_1 = -1, x_2=0, and x_3=1.

The reduced row echelon form is
\left[\begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{,}
which gives the equations
\begin{aligned} x_1 \amp = 2 + x_3 \\ x_2 \amp = -3 + 2x_3 \\ x_4 \amp = -1 - x_3. \\ \end{aligned}
This shows that x_3 is a free variable and x_1, x_2, and x_4 are basic variables. There are therefore infinitely many solutions.

This is not in reduced row echelon form since the leading entry in the second row is not the only nonzero entry in its column. Applying a replacement operation gives,
\left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ \end{array} \right] \sim \left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 5 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ \end{array} \right]\text{.}
There are infinitely many solutions since x_4 is a free variable.

This is not in reduced row echelon form since the leading entries are not all 1. We can scale those rows to find the reduced row echelon form.
\left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array} \right] \sim \left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array} \right]\text{.}
There are no solutions since the last row gives the equation 0=1.

This is not in reduced row echelon form since the leading entry in the last row is not 1 and is not the only nonzero entry in its column.
\left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 3 \\ \end{array} \right] \sim \left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ \end{array} \right]\text{.}
This linear system has a single solution.

This is not in reduced row echelon form since the leading entries appear in the wrong order.
\left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ \end{array} \right] \sim \left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ \end{array} \right]\text{.}
Since x_4 is a free variable, there are infinitely many solutions.

 The reduced row echelon form is

	    \left[
	    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
	    1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 5 \amp 2 \\
	    0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
	    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\
	    \end{array}
	    \right]\text{,}

	  and there are infinitely many solutions.

The reduced row echelon form is
\left[ \begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array} \right]\text{,}
and there are no solutions.

 The reduced row echelon form is

	    \left[
	    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
	    1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	    0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
	    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
	    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
	    \end{array}
	    \right]\text{,}

	  and this linear system has a single solution.

 The reduced row echelon form is

	    \left[
	    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
	    1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
	    0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
	    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
	    \end{array}
	    \right]\text{,}

	  and there are infinitely many solutions.

 Here is an example.

	  \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
	  1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
	  0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
	  0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
	  \end{array}\right]\text{.}

 Here is an example.

