statement.p:
For any given matrix, tells us that there is a reduced row echelon matrix that is row equivalent to it. This exercise demonstrates why this is the case. Each of the following matrices satisfies three of the four conditions required of a reduced row echelon matrix as prescribed by . For each, indicate how a sequence of row operations can be applied to form a row equivalent reduced row echelon matrix.
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ \end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp -4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ \end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{bmatrix}

li.p:
      Interchange the second and third rows to form

	\begin{bmatrix}
	1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
	\end{bmatrix}
	\sim
	\begin{bmatrix}
	1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
	0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	\end{bmatrix}

      Scale the second row by -1/2 to form

	\begin{bmatrix}
	1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
	0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp -4 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
	\end{bmatrix}
	\sim
	\begin{bmatrix}
	1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
	0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
	\end{bmatrix}

This is false. The reduced row echelon form of the augmented matrix could look like
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
In this case, there are three equations in two variables, and the system has exactly one solution.

 This is false, and here is a reduced row echelon
	matrix that illustrates why.

	  \left[\begin{array}{rr|r}
	  1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
	  0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	  \end{array}\right]\text{.}
